{"key":"post-10340710","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10340710</id>\n<content>You lift the wax paper every time you fan, and then put it back on.&amp;nbsp; The purpose of the wax paper is to hold a high humidity of near 100% right at the surface of the substrate/casing layer.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Wax paper doesn't inhibit air exchange if you do it right.&amp;nbsp; You're supposed to crumple it into a ball, and then flatten it back out again.&amp;nbsp; All the wrinkles allow plenty of air to flow underneath.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Replace with a fresh sheet when it gets damp or soggy, but at least every two or three days.&amp;nbsp; Leave in place right through harvest if your grow area suffers from low humidity.&amp;nbsp; The fruits will push it out of the way as they grow.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>10340167</prev>\n<first>10340011</first>\n<last>10340710</last>\n<when>1242361599</when>\n<utime>05/15/09 07:26 AM</utime>\n</post>"}